Here’s a clean, **non-snark**, publication-grade version — the way I would tighten and fuse the ideas into something coherent, sharp, and worthy of the thinkers you’re invoking:

---

**Faith is found by individuals, not manufactured by institutions.**
Organizations can preserve belief, they can even inspire it, but they can also hide behind conformity so thoroughly that the appearance of faith stands in for the thing itself.

Havel named this with brutal accuracy: *“hanging a sign.”*
A symbol placed in the window so others will see it and nod. When every window displays the same sign, the illusion becomes total. It becomes the air the community breathes. And precisely because everyone participates, no one notices.

That is the danger. And the temptation.

**Illusion is the membrane we must break.**
To know illusion is to know that truth has contours.
To feel no illusion is to mistake the surface for the depth.
This is the tension of faith: the human need for what is real and the human talent for disguising it.

It is why Moses could not bear the unveiled face of God.
And it is why Christ came — so the truth that was too radiant to behold could be met in the one thing every human can look upon without fear: a human face.

